Undid revision 1176651032 by [[Special:Contributions/Danbloch|Danbloch]] ([[User talk:Danbloch|talk]]) I would remove the initial source, as it's more subjective. There are some subjective articles that claim the entire series is YA just because the first book is, and because elements of the first book carry through to the rest of the series, but this is not the general consensus.

/* 20th century */The series is YA. The first part of this paragraph is accurate. The first book wasn’t published as YA, but Rowling said, when questioned, that she had no specific intention as to her target audience, and expected the series to age with the characters and “become darker and scarier”, among other such quotes. The accompanying films are mostly PG-13/12 rated.
/* Changing alleged “fairytale” inspiration to “gothic literature” */ new section

/* 20th century */I don’t feel “initially” is misleading - the first book was marketed to middle grade readers and by the third book, there were campaigns marketing them directly to adults. The series began to be placed in multiple age categories in libraries and book stores. This confused marketing scheme came to be because the series slightly predates the common usage of the YA category for speculative fiction titles, and because it originated in the British market, where that age category...

1) The content I’m changing was unsourced to begin with 2) There is ample information on this article and on [[Harry Potter]] about the inspiration taken from Brontë and Dickens. The books bear no meaningful resemblance to fairy tales, and Rowling cites none as specific inspirations for the story.

/* 20th century */It’s true that the first 2 - 3 novels skew younger. However, this seems a somewhat pointless or unhelpful distinction when the series is, by conceit, a coming-of-age story that was marketed to, and found appeal among, a very wide age range. It’s a YA series on average, and at median.

/* Style and allusions */She’s specifically linked to a boom in Young Adult publishing and the solidification of that age category as a viable market for speculative fiction. Her more recent two books fantasy books are for a younger audience than Harry Potter, and are actual children’s fiction.
/* Style and allusions */By how many people? It is clearly not a fairy tale.
The books are not meaningfully influenced by fairy tales and don’t share a fairy tale structure, but they are heavily influenced by such gothic novels as “Wuthering Heights”.
“Good and evil” is not a theme of the series, this is the simplistic moral theme the media has projected onto the series.

When the books were released, they were widely acclaimed. Anyone describing her writing as “conventional” was a minority. This seems like revisionism done to support a more contemporary bias against the author.
Crossover audience makes this generally correct (especially in the British sense), but semantically wrong.
/* Fashion */Shutter shades were an early 2010s trend, as was neon street wear, affiliated mostly with styles popular in the 2000s that crossed over.
He is a citizen of the US and has an American father. This isn’t ambiguous.
Source? Not everything needs to be segregated by ethnicity/race
/* U.S. censor */It did not receive a “milder” equivalent rating in the UK.
/* Central Texas */Corn syrup is a processed ingredient. Not a traditional ingredient of the sauce
/* Race and ethnicity */There is no “Anglo” census designation, and this is misleading
